In [161]:
def dbplot(j,i,z):
    y = wisc.diagnosis == "M"
    X = np.column_stack((j, i))
    m = KNeighborsClassifier(z)
    e = m.fit(X, y)
    ex1 = np.linspace(j.min(), j.max(), 100)
    ex2 = np.linspace(i.min(), i.min(), 100)
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
    g = np.column_stack((xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()))
    haty = m.predict(g).reshape(100,100)
    _=plt.imshow(haty, extent=(j.min(), j.max(), i.min(), i.max()),
                 aspect = "auto",
                 interpolation="none", origin="lower",
                 alpha=0.3)
    _ = plt.scatter(j,i,c=y, edgecolor="k", s=8)
    _ = plt.show()
dbplot(wisc['texture.mean'], wisc['concpoints.mean'], 7)

X = wisc[['texture.mean','concpoints.mean']].values
y = wisc.diagnosis.values
V = np.cov(X, rowvar=False)
m = KNeighborsClassifier(7, metric='mahalanobis', metric_params={"V":V})
_ = m.fit(X, y)
def newdb(j, i ,z):    
    y = wisc.diagnosis == "M"
    X = np.column_stack((j, i))
    V = np.cov(X, rowvar=False)
    m = KNeighborsClassifier(7, metric='mahalanobis', metric_params={"V":V})
    e = m.fit(X, y)
    ex1 = np.linspace(j.min(), j.max(), 100)
    ex2 = np.linspace(i.min(), i.min(), 100)
    xx1, xx2 = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
    g = np.column_stack((xx1.ravel(), xx2.ravel()))
    haty = m.predict(g).reshape(100,100)
    _=plt.imshow(haty, extent=(j.min(), j.max(), i.min(), i.max()),
                 aspect = "auto",
                 interpolation="none", origin="lower",
                 alpha=0.3)
    _ = plt.scatter(j,i,c=y, edgecolor="k", s=8)
    _ = plt.show()
newdb(wisc['texture.mean'], wisc['concpoints.mean'], 7)
cv = cross_val_score(m, X, y, cv=10)
cv.mean()
Out[168]:
0.9261278195488721

6¶

It seems that the accuracy scores follow the same pattern, with the original data having the lowest score, the normalized being the second highest, and the mahalnobis as the highest accuracy. This may depend on features, however the ones that I tested all followed the same trend. I can't really tell if the visuals align with the cross validation results, as all the graphs' apect ratios are auto'ed.

  • b. M represents the columns for each color channel, this numebr is derrived from multiplying the columns by rows from the shape described above.
  • c. cl[?] is finding the cluster id for each pixel.
  • d. Center color value coloumns represent the RGB colorspace, it shows what color pixels are at certain locations.
  • e. There are 16 different center color values becuase we turned this image into one that only has 16 color values.

2 colors¶

In [188]:
pixels = imread("../data/a5f8962c478595cbf3b9e7a7a06f3afa.jpg")
ax = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
ax.set_aspect("equal")
_ = plt.imshow(pixels)
M = pixels.reshape((-1,pixels.shape[2]))
print(M.shape)
def colors(e):    
    m = KMeans(e).fit(M) # cluster the color values
    cl = m.predict(M) # find the cluster id for each pixel
    centers = m.cluster_centers_ # find the cluster centers (i.e. colors)
    print("center color values:\n", centers)
    compressed = centers[cl]/255 # normalize to between 0 and 1
    compressed = compressed.reshape(pixels.shape)
    # make it back to NxM array
    ax = plt.subplot(1,1,1)
    ax.set_aspect("equal")
    _ = plt.imshow(compressed)
    _ = plt.show()
colors(2)
